# Fluff Date: 2026-02-17 11:57:30
overview:<p>The No-Dachi was introduced in 3058 by the Cosby BattleMech Research Firm on Vega as the Draconis Combine's answer to the growing proliferation of melee-equipped BattleMechs fielded by the Federated Commonwealth. Named for the legendary oversized Japanese sword, the seventy-ton heavy 'Mech served as a testbed for two emerging technologies: the BattleMech-scale sword and Triple Strength Myomer. The samurai culture deeply ingrained in Combine MechWarriors made them resistant to the hatchets favored by Commonwealth designs, prompting Cosby engineers to develop a more elegant melee weapon befitting the Combine's warrior traditions. Working in close cooperation with the Eleventh Legion of Vega, which provided advanced technologies and technical expertise, Cosby created a dangerous close-combat design that paired devastating melee capability with respectable ranged firepower.</p>

capabilities:<p>The No-Dachi is built around its seven-meter katana-style sword, a weapon made truly devastating by the 'Mech's Triple Strength Myomer system. When running hot, the myomers dramatically increase the No-Dachi's striking power and boost its speed from 86 to 97 kilometers per hour, making it a fearsome opponent in close quarters. This heat dependency shapes the entire combat philosophy of the design, as pilots must carefully manage their thermal output to maximize myomer performance.</p><p>At range, the Lord's Light 2 extended-range PPC provides the primary long-range striking power, capable of softening targets as the No-Dachi closes the distance. The dual Shigunga MRM-20 racks deliver devastating medium-range barrages, though their inherent inaccuracy stands in stark contrast to the precision of the katana. A Guided Technologies SRM-2, Telos-4 SRM-4, and Diverse Optics medium laser round out the close-range arsenal, providing supplementary firepower and crucial heat generation to activate the myomers.</p><p>Riding on a Magna 350 XL engine, the No-Dachi achieves respectable speed for a seventy-ton design, though the extra-light engine's vulnerability to side torso hits represents a significant weakness. Starshield A armor provides adequate protection, but pilots must be mindful that sustained exchanges of fire can expose the design's limitations before it reaches melee range.</p>

deployment:<p>Based on the NDA-2KO, this variant removes the rear-firing right torso laser to install a C3 slave computer, enabling the No-Dachi to share targeting data with lance mates while closing to melee range. Initially a field modification popular with DCMS units, the variant proved so successful that it entered standard factory production at Cosby's Kajikazawa facility after the Jihad, marking it as one of the few field refits to achieve full production status.</p>

history:<p>The No-Dachi's development traces back to the mid-3050s, when the Cosby Myomer Research Firm—then primarily a myomer component supplier—partnered with the Eleventh Legion of Vega to develop a new close-combat BattleMech. The Legion, known for its technical expertise and its famous former commander Theodore Kurita, provided Cosby with advanced technologies and research support. In exchange, Cosby agreed to allocate half of all No-Dachi production to the Legion's ranks.</p><p>The design entered service in 3058 and quickly became synonymous with the Legion of Vega. Through special arrangement with Cosby, the bulk of No-Dachis were assigned to the Eleventh Legion, though several battalions' worth were distributed to other front-line DCMS units by the time of the FedCom Civil War. The design's association with the Legion proved a double-edged sword; Sword of Light regiments and other prestigious formations largely avoided the No-Dachi, preferring to lobby for a melee-capable 'Mech untainted by the Legion's reputation.</p><p>When the Word of Blake launched its invasion of Vega during the Jihad, the Draconis Combine ordered Cosby to relocate its production facilities deeper into the Combine. The company moved to Kajikazawa in the Benjamin Military District, an impressive logistical feat accomplished during wartime. By 3079, production lines were running at capacity, though a shortage of shipping infrastructure on the formerly backwater world initially hampered distribution. The bulk of output during this period went to the Second Benjamin Regulars tasked with defending Kajikazawa and the company's facilities.</p><p>The relocation proved fortuitous, as the Kajikazawa facility received significant government funding to develop experimental technologies, ultimately producing the NDA-3X prototype. The No-Dachi's prominence continued into the Dark Age, with senior DCMS commanders continuing to favor the design for frontline service. The Kajikazawa facility remained active through the ilClan era, producing updated variants including the NDA-3S Lyran export model, ensuring the No-Dachi's continued service across multiple factions and eras.</p>

